Quadratic functions are often expressed in vertex form:

\[y~=~a(x-h)^2+k\]

From the graph below, determine the values of the 3 parameters.


  • \(a=\)
  • \(h=\)
  • \(k=\)

Based on function transformations, it should be clear that the vertex is at point \((h,k)\) and parameter \(a\) dictates the vertical stretch and possible vertical reflection (which flips the parabola upside down, such that it looks like a hill, not a valley).

When determining \(a\) from a graph, it is easiest to identify the point on the curve 1 unit to the right of the vertex. That point will be at \((h+1,k+a)\). By subtracting the \(y\) value of the vertex from the \(y\) value of that point 1 unit to the right, it is easy to find \(a\).


\[(6)-(4)~=~ 2\]

So,

  • \(a=2\)
  • \(h=-1\)
  • \(k=4\)

Thus, the equation of the curve is: \[y~=~2(x+1)^2+4\]

A transformed square-root function was constructed by randomly choosing integers for the values of \(m\), \(p\), \(h\), and \(k\) in the equation below.

\[y~=~m\sqrt{\frac{1}{p}(x-h)}+k\]

The equation's curve is plotted below:


Notice, I've marked where the curve intersects the lattice points exactly. These points are where \(x\) and \(y\) are both integers. (On the midterm, these points might not be marked.)

Find the values of the parameters:

  • \(m=\)
  • \(p=\)
  • \(h=\)
  • \(k=\)

I recommend opening up Desmos and typing in \(y~=~m\sqrt{\frac{1}{p}(x-h)}+k\), using sliders for \(m\), \(p\), \(h\), and \(k\). Then see what happens as you adjust each slider. You might also add points \((h,k)\) and \((h+p,k+m)\) to see where those move.

The given equation represents a transformation that is best thought of as stretches and then shifts. Imagine the parent function stretched vertically by factor \(m\) and horizontally by factor \(p\). Then, the parent function is shifted horizontally by distance \(h\) and vertically by distance \(k\).

The parent function, \(y=\sqrt{x}\), has its endpoint at the origin. This point on the curve is unaffected by the stretches, so its corresponding point at \((7,-6)\) represents the shifts only.

\[h=7\] \[k=-6\]

The parent function also goes through \((1,1)\). Because both stretches are integer multipliers, we know the corresponding point will be a lattice point on the curve. This key lattice point on the curve is at \((4,-4)\). We can find \(m\) and \(p\) by comparing this point to the endpoint.


  • \(m=2\)
  • \(p=-3\)
  • \(h=7\)
  • \(k=-6\)
